metadata.name: Computed Scenery #74
metadata.description:
I spent my college years living in a place near mountains and the sea. It was my dream to use mathematics and algorithms to describe a fantastically beautiful world in my hometown.

This piece was originally an audio-visual artwork. But after a few years, I rewrote it as a piece of generative art.

I hope you will like it.

- Made with P5js
- Press 's' to save the artwork

metadata.name: Eyeshadow Roses #823
metadata.description:
"Eyeshadow Roses" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Painterly roses randomly overprinted with heavy streaks of ink. 

The roses grow by a sequence of three spirals, every new spiral smaller and superimposed on the former.  After the roses are fully formed, a random mask of heavy ink is algorithmically screened over the flowers in a pattern of horizontal or vertical lines, occasionally fully flooding the painting. The accumulation of choices evokes graffiti or printmaking. The sequence of choices are interpreted by the computer according to the algorithm. The beauty of these choices are determined by the viewer.

Each piece takes roughly 10 seconds to generate.

Artist: @sarah_ridgley
Press [s] to save the image
JavaScript / p5js | script size: 11kb

metadata.name: a necessary reaction #125
metadata.description:
This piece has an interesting (to me) history. I originally started by trying to clone my IRL physical painting style in Midjourney. I got very close, then I had the idea to make a generative piece that could recreate the Midjourney recreation of my physical paintings. 

As is the nature of things, this result has departed quite a bit from my original intentions. You can scroll through the last two weeks of my Twitter feed to follow the entire process and see the original source. During the course of this writing process, crypto crashed, and the piece got darker and darker. 

There are certain combinations which will result on a matte black on matte black image (that I've taken to calling "carbon mode." A mint is in carbon mode when both palettes are 1, with a gesture on top. This is definitely the darkest mint I've done for FxHash, or even in general, and matches my mood as I watch my net worth drill to the core of the Earth. I am, however, an optimist, and I fully expect to look back on this month and laugh. Hopefully in the not-too-distant future.

metadata.name: Digital Surface 1 #16
metadata.description:
The mechanics of Digital Surface is inspired by nature and the aesthetics by pixels. Digital Surface is an attempt to find an autonomous visual logic for a digital world made by machines.
The image is created one pixel after another, calculating the proceeding pixel based on the previous generations.
The color palettes are influenced by colors occurring in nature mixed with artificial man made colors that we see more today, aiming to look for new combinations that are pleasant to humans and natively digital.

Render time can be long. Once the image is completed, press "s" to save in a small size, "m" in a medium, "l" in a large, "x" in a xlarge and "w" to save with the size of the window.

Digital Surface is a 5 series project. Each Series is released singularly, the first being Digital Surface 1. The main differentiation for series 1 is that each image contains 2 colors.
This is Francesco Forcellini Studio's first NFT project broadening their field of work from physical to digital.

Built using p5js, published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.

Once the collection will be fully minted, the variations button will be disabled.

metadata.description:
Every token can output in 12 different aspect ratios:
1x1, 3x1, 3x2, 2x3, 4x3, 3x4, 5x4, 4x5, 16x9, 9x16, 16x10, 10x16

With 3 framing options:
1. No frame
2. Rectangle frame
3. Arched window

And downloadable in 4 different resolutions:
1. 1000px
2. 2000px
3. 4000px
4. 8000px

Click on the image in live view to unlock all these possibilities.
